# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: simplex-method-pivoting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] In mathematical optimization, **Bland's rule** (also known as **Bland's algorithm**, **Bland's anti-cycling rule** or **Bland's pivot rule**) is an algorithmic refinement of the simplex method for linear optimization.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] With Bland's rule, the simplex algorithm solves feasible linear optimization problems without cycling.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] The original simplex algorithm starts with an arbitrary basic feasible solution, and then changes the basis in order to decrease the minimization target and find an optimal solution.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] Usually, the target indeed decreases in every step, and thus after a bounded number of steps an optimal solution is found.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] However, there are examples of degenerate linear programs, on which the original simplex algorithm cycles forever.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] It gets stuck at a basic feasible solution (a corner of the feasible polytope) and changes bases in a cyclic way without decreasing the minimization target.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] Such cycles are avoided by Bland's rule for choosing a column to enter and a column to leave the basis.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] Bland while he was a research fellow at the Center for Operations Research and Econometrics in Belgium.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] One uses Bland's rule during an iteration of the simplex method to decide first what column (known as the *entering variable*) and then row (known as the *leaving variable*) in the tableau to pivot on.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] Now among the rows, choose the one with the lowest ratio between the (transformed) right-hand side and the coefficient in the pivot tableau where the coefficient is greater than zero.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] If the minimum ratio is shared by several rows, choose the row with the lowest-numbered column (variable) basic in it.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] It can be formally proven that, with Bland's selection rule, the simplex algorithm never cycles; therefore, it is guaranteed to terminate within a bounded time.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] While Bland's pivot rule is theoretically important, from a practical perspective, it is quite inefficient and takes a long time to converge (for example, the simplex method applied to the Klee-Minty cube).
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] In practice, other pivot rules are used, and cycling rarely happens.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] In the abstract setting of oriented matroids, Bland's rule cycles on some examples.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] A restricted class of oriented matroids on which Bland's rule avoids cycling has been termed "Bland oriented matroids" by Jack Edmonds.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/bland-s-rule] Another pivoting rule, the criss-cross algorithm, avoids cycles on all oriented-matroid linear-programs.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] In mathematical optimization, the **criss-cross algorithm** is any of a family of algorithms for linear programming.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Variants of the criss-cross algorithm also solve more general problems with linear inequality constraints and nonlinear objective functions; there are criss-cross algorithms for linear-fractional programming problems, quadratic-programming problems, and linear complementarity problems.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Dantzig, the criss-cross algorithm is not a polynomial-time algorithm for linear programming.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Both algorithms visit all 2*D* corners of a (perturbed) cube in dimension *D*, the Klee–Minty cube (after Victor Klee and George J.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] However, when it is started at a random corner, the criss-cross algorithm on average visits only *D* additional corners.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Thus, for the three-dimensional cube, the algorithm visits all 8 corners in the worst case and exactly 3 additional corners on average.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm was published independently by Tamas Terlaky and by Zhe-Min Wang; related algorithms appeared in unpublished reports by other authors.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] In linear programming, the criss-cross algorithm pivots between a sequence of bases but differs from the simplex algorithm.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm is simpler than the simplex algorithm, because the criss-cross algorithm only has one phase.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Its pivoting rules are similar to the least-index pivoting rule of Bland.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Bland's rule selects an entering variables by comparing values of reduced costs, using the real-number ordering of the eligible pivots.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Unlike Bland's rule, the criss-cross algorithm is "purely combinatorial", selecting an entering variable and a leaving variable by considering only the signs of coefficients rather than their real-number ordering.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm has been applied to furnish constructive proofs of basic results in linear algebra, such as the lemma of Farkas.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] While most simplex variants are monotonic in the objective (strictly in the non-degenerate case), most variants of the criss-cross algorithm lack a monotone merit function which can be a disadvantage in practice.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm works on a standard pivot tableau (or on-the-fly calculated parts of a tableau, if implemented like the revised simplex method).
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] In a general step, if the tableau is primal or dual infeasible, it selects one of the infeasible rows / columns as the pivot row / column using an index selection rule.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] An important property is that the selection is made on the union of the infeasible indices and the standard version of the algorithm does not distinguish column and row indices (that is, the column indices basic in the rows).
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] If a row is selected then the algorithm uses the index selection rule to identify a position to a dual type pivot, while if a column is selected then it uses the index selection rule to find a row position and carries out a primal type pivot.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The time complexity of an algorithm counts the number of arithmetic operations sufficient for the algorithm to solve the problem.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] For example, Gaussian elimination requires on the order of*D*3 operations, and so it is said to have polynomial time-complexity, because its complexity is bounded by a cubic polynomial.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] There are examples of algorithms that do not have polynomial-time complexity.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] For example, a generalization of Gaussian elimination called Buchberger's algorithm has for its complexity an exponential function of the problem data (the degree of the polynomials and the number of variables of the multivariate polynomials).
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Because exponential functions eventually grow much faster than polynomial functions, an exponential complexity implies that an algorithm has slow performance on large problems.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Several algorithms for linear programming—Khachiyan's ellipsoidal algorithm, Karmarkar's projective algorithm, and central-path algorithms—have polynomial time-complexity (in the worst case and thus on average).
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The ellipsoidal and projective algorithms were published before the criss-cross algorithm.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] However, like the simplex algorithm of Dantzig, the criss-cross algorithm is *not* a polynomial-time algorithm for linear programming.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Terlaky's criss-cross algorithm visits all the 2*D* corners of a (perturbed) cube in dimension *D*, according to a paper of Roos; Roos's paper modifies the Klee–Minty construction of a cube on which the simplex algorithm takes 2*D* steps.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Like the simplex algorithm, the criss-cross algorithm visits all 8 corners of the three-dimensional cube in the worst case.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] When it is initialized at a random corner of the cube, the criss-cross algorithm visits only *D* additional corners, however, according to a 1994 paper by Fukuda and Namiki.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Trivially, the simplex algorithm takes on average *D* steps for a cube.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Like the simplex algorithm, the criss-cross algorithm visits exactly 3 additional corners of the three-dimensional cube on average.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm has been extended to solve more general problems than linear programming problems.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] A sufficient matrix is a generalization both of a positive-definite matrix and of a P-matrix, whose principal minors are each positive.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm has been adapted also for linear-fractional programming.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm was used in an algorithm for enumerating all the vertices of a polytope, which was published by David Avis and Komei Fukuda in 1992.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm is often studied using the theory of oriented matroids (OMs), which is a combinatorial abstraction of linear-optimization theory.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Indeed, Bland's pivoting rule was based on his previous papers on oriented-matroid theory.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] However, Bland's rule exhibits cycling on some oriented-matroid linear-programming problems.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The first purely combinatorial algorithm for linear programming was devised by Michael J.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Todd's algorithm was developed not only for linear-programming in the setting of oriented matroids, but also for quadratic-programming problems and linear-complementarity problems.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Todd's algorithm is complicated even to state, unfortunately, and its finite-convergence proofs are somewhat complicated.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm and its proof of finite termination can be simply stated and readily extend the setting of oriented matroids.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The algorithm can be further simplified for *linear feasibility problems*, that is for linear systems with nonnegative variables; these problems can be formulated for oriented matroids.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm has been adapted for problems that are more complicated than linear programming: There are oriented-matroid variants also for the quadratic-programming problem and for the linear-complementarity problem.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm is a simply stated algorithm for linear programming.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] It was the second fully combinatorial algorithm for linear programming.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The partially combinatorial simplex algorithm of Bland cycles on some (nonrealizable) oriented matroids.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The first fully combinatorial algorithm was published by Todd, and it is also like the simplex algorithm in that it preserves feasibility after the first feasible basis is generated; however, Todd's rule is complicated.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm is not a simplex-like algorithm, because it need not maintain feasibility.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm does not have polynomial time-complexity, however.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Researchers have extended the criss-cross algorithm for many optimization-problems, including linear-fractional programming.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] The criss-cross algorithm can solve quadratic programming problems and linear complementarity problems, even in the setting of oriented matroids.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/criss-cross-algorithm] Even when generalized, the criss-cross algorithm remains simply stated.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] The Dantzig-Wolfe decomposition considers the following initial linear program.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] The decomposition starts by reformulating the problem. the constraint $Bx\leq b$ is equivalently reformulating by writing x as a convex combination of points satisfying $Bx\leq b$ .
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] This leads to the following linear program.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] Here the new variables $\lambda _{i}$ represent the coefficient in the convex combination, and the coefficients $x_{i}$ represent the points satisfying $Bx\leq b$ .
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] In order to be exact, the formulation needs to contain one variable $\lambda _{i}$ for each extreme point of the polyhedron induced by $Bx\leq b$ .
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] This is because every point of a non-empty, bounded convex polyhedron can be represented as a convex combination of its extreme points.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] This leads to an intractable number of variables.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] In order to be able to solve this new formulation containing an intractable number of variables, one use the column generation algorithm.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] This leads to an iterative algorithm where a couple $(\lambda _{i},x_{i})$ is generated at every iteration.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] The whole algorithm can be summarized as follows.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] The main use case for the Dantzig–Wolfe decomposition is when the constraint matrix of the linear program has the following 'almost diagonal' structure visualized below.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] Here, the set of constraints *D* is usually be identified as "connecting", "coupling", or "complicating" constraints.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] Meanwhile each constraint block *$F_{i}$* is going to be reformulated using the Dantig-Wolfe method.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] This leads to one sub-problem for each block $F_{i}$ .
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] The two main reasons why the Dantzig-Wolfe method works especially well in this case are the following.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] First, each block $F_{i}$ only applies to a subset of the variables.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] This means the corresponding sub-problem will be a lot smaller than the original problem (less constraints **and** less variables) which means it can be solved faster.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] Second, although the sub-problem can always be solved independently, in the case of a diagonal structure the sub-problems are usually less linked.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] Indeed, suppose that $F_{1}$ and $F_{2}$ share a variable $x_{1}$ , then they have to 'agree' on the value of $x_{1}$ .
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] This means every time the $F_{1}$ sub-problem proposes a new point with a different value for $x_{1}$ , the $F_{2}$ sub-problem also has to generate a new point with an agreeing value for $x_{1}$ .
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] There are examples of the implementation of Dantzig–Wolfe decomposition available in the closed source AMPL and GAMS mathematical modeling software.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] There are general, parallel, and fast implementations available as open-source software, including some provided by JuMP and the GNU Linear Programming Kit.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] The algorithm can be implemented such that the subproblems are solved in parallel, since their solutions are completely independent.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] When this is the case, there are options for the master program as to how the columns should be integrated into the master.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] The master may wait until each subproblem has completed and then incorporate all columns that improve the objective or it may choose a smaller subset of those columns.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] Another option is that the master may take only the first available column and then stop and restart all of the subproblems with new objectives based upon the incorporation of the newest column.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] Another design choice for implementation involves columns that exit the basis at each iteration of the algorithm.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] Those columns may be retained, immediately discarded, or discarded via some policy after future iterations (for example, remove all non-basic columns every 10 iterations).
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/dantzig-wolfe-decomposition] A (2001) computational evaluation of Dantzig-Wolfe in general and Dantzig-Wolfe and parallel computation is the PhD thesis by J.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] The **Klee–Minty cube** or **Klee–Minty polytope** (named after Victor Klee and George J.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] Minty) is a unit hypercube of variable dimension whose corners have been perturbed.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] Klee and Minty demonstrated that George Dantzig's simplex algorithm has poor worst-case performance when initialized at one corner of their "squashed cube".
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] On the three-dimensional version, the simplex algorithm and the criss-cross algorithm visit all 8 corners in the worst case.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] In particular, many optimization algorithms for linear optimization exhibit poor performance when applied to the Klee–Minty cube.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] In 1973 Klee and Minty showed that Dantzig's simplex algorithm was not a polynomial-time algorithm when applied to their cube.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] Later, modifications of the Klee–Minty cube have shown poor behavior both for other basis-exchange pivoting algorithms and also for interior-point algorithms.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] The Klee–Minty cube was originally specified with a parameterized system of linear inequalities, with the dimension as the parameter.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] The cube in two-dimensional space is a *squashed square*, and the "cube" in three-dimensional space is a *squashed cube*.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] Illustrations of the "cube" have appeared besides algebraic descriptions.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] This has D variables, D constraints other than the D non-negativity constraints, and $2^{D}$ vertices, just as a D -dimensional hypercube does.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] If the objective function to be maximized is $2^{D-1}x_{1}+2^{D-2}x_{2}+\dots +2x_{D-1}+x_{D},$ and if the initial vertex for the simplex algorithm is the origin, then the algorithm as formulated by Dantzig visits all $2^{D}$ vertices, finally reaching the optimal vertex $(0,0,\dots ,5^{D})$ .
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] The Klee–Minty cube has been used to analyze the performance of many algorithms, both in the worst case and on average.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] For example, Gaussian elimination requires the order of $D^{3}$ operations, and so it is said to have polynomial time-complexity because its complexity is bounded by a cubic polynomial.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] In mathematical optimization, the Klee–Minty cube is an example that shows the worst-case computational complexity of many algorithms of linear optimization.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] It is a deformed cube with exactly 2*D* corners in dimension D .
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] Klee and Minty showed that Dantzig's simplex algorithm visits all corners of a (perturbed) cube in dimension D in the worst case.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] Modifications of the Klee–Minty construction showed similar exponential time complexity for other pivoting rules of simplex type, which maintain primal feasibility, such as Bland's rule.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] Another modification showed that the criss-cross algorithm, which does not maintain primal feasibility, also visits all the corners of a modified Klee–Minty cube.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] Further modifications of the Klee–Minty cube have shown the poor performance of central-path–following algorithms for linear optimization, in that the central path comes arbitrarily close to each of the corners of a cube.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] This "vertex-stalking" performance is surprising because such path-following algorithms have polynomial-time complexity for linear optimization.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] The Klee–Minty cube has also inspired research on average-case complexity.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] When eligible pivots are made randomly (and not by the rule of steepest descent), Dantzig's simplex algorithm needs on average quadratically many steps (on the order of $O(D^{2})$ .
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] Standard variants of the simplex algorithm take on average D steps for a cube.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] However according to Fukuda & Namiki (1994), when it is initialized at a random corner of the cube, the criss-cross algorithm visits only D additional corners.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/klee-minty-cube] Both the simplex algorithm and the criss-cross algorithm visit exactly 3 additional corners of the three-dimensional cube on average.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] In mathematical optimization, the **revised simplex method** is a variant of George Dantzig's simplex method for linear programming.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] The revised simplex method is mathematically equivalent to the standard simplex method but differs in implementation.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] Instead of maintaining a tableau which explicitly represents the constraints adjusted to a set of basic variables, it maintains a representation of a basis of the matrix representing the constraints.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] The matrix-oriented approach allows for greater computational efficiency by enabling sparse matrix operations.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] Without loss of generality, it is assumed that the constraint matrix ***A*** has full row rank and that the problem is feasible, i.e., there is at least one ***x*** ≥ **0** such that ***Ax*** = ***b***.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] If ***A*** is rank-deficient, either there are redundant constraints, or the problem is infeasible.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] Both situations can be handled by a presolve step.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] For linear programming, the Karush–Kuhn–Tucker conditions are both necessary and sufficient for optimality.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] where ***λ*** and ***s*** are the Lagrange multipliers associated with the constraints ***Ax*** = ***b*** and ***x*** ≥ **0**, respectively.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] The last condition, which is equivalent to *sixi* = 0 for all 1 < *i* < *n*, is called the *complementary slackness condition*.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] By what is sometimes known as the *fundamental theorem of linear programming*, a vertex ***x*** of the feasible polytope can be identified by being a basis ***B*** of ***A*** chosen from the latter's columns.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] Since ***A*** has full rank, ***B*** is nonsingular.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] To satisfy the complementary slackness condition, let ***sB*** = **0**.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] If ***sN*** ≥ **0** at this point, the KKT conditions are satisfied, and thus ***x*** is optimal.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] If the KKT conditions are violated, a *pivot operation* consisting of introducing a column of ***N*** into the basis at the expense of an existing column in ***B*** is performed.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] In the absence of degeneracy, a pivot operation always results in a strict decrease in ***c***T***x***.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] Therefore, if the problem is bounded, the revised simplex method must terminate at an optimal vertex after repeated pivot operations because there are only a finite number of vertices.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] Select an index *m* < *q* ≤ *n* such that *sq* < 0 as the *entering index*.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] The corresponding column of ***A***, ***A**q*, will be moved into the basis, and *xq* will be allowed to increase from zero.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] i.e., every unit increase in *xq* results in a decrease by −*sq* in ***c***T***x***.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] initially, which corresponds to a feasible vertex ***x*** = [0 0 0 10 15]T.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] Then ***d*** = [1 3]T, which means a unit increase in *x*3 results in *x*4 and *x*5 being decreased by 1 and 3, respectively.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] Therefore, *x*3 is increased to 5, at which point *x*5 is reduced to zero, and *p* = 5 becomes the leaving index.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] A positive ***sN*** indicates that ***x*** is now optimal.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] Because the revised simplex method is mathematically equivalent to the simplex method, it also suffers from degeneracy, where a pivot operation does not result in a decrease in ***c***T***x***, and a chain of pivot operations causes the basis to cycle.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] A perturbation or lexicographic strategy can be used to prevent cycling and guarantee termination.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] Instead of refactorizing ***B***, usually an LU factorization is directly updated after each pivot operation, for which purpose there exist several strategies such as the Forrest−Tomlin and Bartels−Golub methods.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/revised-simplex-method] However, the amount of data representing the updates as well as numerical errors builds up over time and makes periodic refactorization necessary.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In mathematical optimization, Dantzig's **simplex algorithm** (or **simplex method**) is an algorithm for linear programming.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The name of the algorithm is derived from the concept of a simplex and was suggested by T.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Simplices are not actually used in the method, but one interpretation of it is that it operates on simplicial *cones*, and these become proper simplices with an additional constraint.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The simplicial cones in question are the corners (i.e., the neighborhoods of the vertices) of a geometric object called a polytope.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The shape of this polytope is defined by the constraints applied to the objective function.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] George Dantzig worked on planning methods for the US Army Air Force during World War II using a desk calculator.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] During 1946, his colleague challenged him to mechanize the planning process to distract him from taking another job.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Dantzig formulated the problem as linear inequalities inspired by the work of Wassily Leontief, however, at that time he didn't include an objective as part of his formulation.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Without an objective, a vast number of solutions can be feasible, and therefore to find the "best" feasible solution, military-specified "ground rules" must be used that describe how goals can be achieved as opposed to specifying a goal itself.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Dantzig's core insight was to realize that most such ground rules can be translated into a linear objective function that needs to be maximized.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Development of the simplex method was evolutionary and happened over a period of about a year.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] After Dantzig included an objective function as part of his formulation during mid-1947, the problem was mathematically more tractable.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Dantzig realized that one of the unsolved problems that he had mistaken as homework in his professor Jerzy Neyman's class (and actually later solved), was applicable to finding an algorithm for linear programs.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This problem involved finding the existence of Lagrange multipliers for general linear programs over a continuum of variables, each bounded between zero and one, and satisfying linear constraints expressed in the form of Lebesgue integrals.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Dantzig later published his "homework" as a thesis to earn his doctorate.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The column geometry used in this thesis gave Dantzig insight that made him believe that the Simplex method would be very efficient.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] There is a straightforward process to convert any linear program into one in standard form, so using this form of linear programs results in no loss of generality.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In geometric terms, the feasible region defined by all values of $\mathbf {x}$ such that ${\textstyle A\mathbf {x} \leq \mathbf {b} }$ and $\forall i,x_{i}\geq 0$ is a (possibly unbounded) convex polytope.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] An extreme point or vertex of this polytope is known as *basic feasible solution* (BFS).
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] It can be shown that for a linear program in standard form, if the objective function has a maximum value on the feasible region, then it has this value on (at least) one of the extreme points.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This in itself reduces the problem to a finite computation since there is a finite number of extreme points, but the number of extreme points is unmanageably large for all but the smallest linear programs.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] It can also be shown that, if an extreme point is not a maximum point of the objective function, then there is an edge containing the point so that the value of the objective function is strictly increasing on the edge moving away from the point.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] If the edge is finite, then the edge connects to another extreme point where the objective function has a greater value, otherwise the objective function is unbounded above on the edge and the linear program has no solution.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The simplex algorithm applies this insight by walking along edges of the polytope to extreme points with greater and greater objective values.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This continues until the maximum value is reached, or an unbounded edge is visited (concluding that the problem has no solution).
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The algorithm always terminates because the number of vertices in the polytope is finite; moreover since we jump between vertices always in the same direction (that of the objective function), we hope that the number of vertices visited will be small.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The solution of a linear program is accomplished in two steps.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In the first step, known as Phase I, a starting extreme point is found.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Depending on the nature of the program this may be trivial, but in general it can be solved by applying the simplex algorithm to a modified version of the original program.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The possible results of Phase I are either that a basic feasible solution is found or that the feasible region is empty.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In the latter case the linear program is called *infeasible*.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In the second step, Phase II, the simplex algorithm is applied using the basic feasible solution found in Phase I as a starting point.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The possible results from Phase II are either an optimum basic feasible solution or an infinite edge on which the objective function is unbounded above.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The transformation of a linear program to one in standard form may be accomplished as follows.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] First, for each variable with a lower bound other than 0, a new variable is introduced representing the difference between the variable and bound.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The original variable can then be eliminated by substitution.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The second equation may be used to eliminate $x_{1}$ from the linear program.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In this way, all lower bound constraints may be changed to non-negativity restrictions.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Second, for each remaining inequality constraint, a new variable, called a *slack variable*, is introduced to change the constraint to an equality constraint.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This variable represents the difference between the two sides of the inequality and is assumed to be non-negative.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] It is much easier to perform algebraic manipulation on inequalities in this form.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In inequalities where ≥ appears such as the second one, some authors refer to the variable introduced as a *surplus variable*.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Third, each unrestricted variable is eliminated from the linear program.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This can be done in two ways, one is by solving for the variable in one of the equations in which it appears and then eliminating the variable by substitution.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The other is to replace the variable with the difference of two restricted variables.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The equation may be used to eliminate $z_{1}$ from the linear program.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] It is also useful to assume that the rank of $\mathbf {A}$ is the number of rows.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This results in no loss of generality since otherwise either the system $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ has redundant equations which can be dropped, or the system is inconsistent and the linear program has no solution.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The first row defines the objective function and the remaining rows specify the constraints.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The zero in the first column represents the zero vector of the same dimension as the vector $\mathbf {b}$ (different authors use different conventions as to the exact layout).
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] If the columns of $\mathbf {A}$ can be rearranged so that it contains the identity matrix of order p (the number of rows in $\mathbf {A}$ ) then the tableau is said to be in *canonical form*.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The variables corresponding to the columns of the identity matrix are called *basic variables* while the remaining variables are called *nonbasic* or *free variables*.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] If the values of the nonbasic variables are set to 0, then the values of the basic variables are easily obtained as entries in $\mathbf {b}$ and this solution is a basic feasible solution.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The algebraic interpretation here is that the coefficients of the linear equation represented by each row are either 0 , 1 , or some other number.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Each row will have 1 column with value 1 , $p-1$ columns with coefficients 0 , and the remaining columns with some other coefficients (these other variables represent our non-basic variables).
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] By setting the values of the non-basic variables to zero we ensure in each row that the value of the variable represented by a 1 in its column is equal to the b value at that row.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Conversely, given a basic feasible solution, the columns corresponding to the nonzero variables can be expanded to a nonsingular matrix B .
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] If the corresponding tableau is multiplied by the inverse of B , then the result is a tableau in canonical form.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] be a tableau in canonical form, where ${\widehat {\mathbf {b} }}=B^{-1}\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Additional row-addition transformations can be applied to remove the coefficients **c**T *B* from the objective function.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] where *z**B* is the value of the objective function at the corresponding basic feasible solution.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The updated coefficients, also known as *relative cost coefficients*, are the rates of change of the objective function with respect to the nonbasic variables.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The geometrical operation of moving from a basic feasible solution to an adjacent basic feasible solution is implemented as a *pivot operation*.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] First, a nonzero *pivot element* is selected in a nonbasic column.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The row containing this element is multiplied by its reciprocal to change this element to 1, and then multiples of the row are added to the other rows to change the other entries in the column to 0.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The result is that, if the pivot element is in a row *r*, then the column becomes the *r*-th column of the identity matrix.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The variable for this column is now a basic variable, replacing the variable which corresponded to the *r*-th column of the identity matrix before the operation.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In effect, the variable corresponding to the pivot column enters the set of basic variables and is called the *entering variable*, and the variable being replaced leaves the set of basic variables and is called the *leaving variable*.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The tableau is still in canonical form but with the set of basic variables changed by one element.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Let a linear program be given by a canonical tableau.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The simplex algorithm proceeds by performing successive pivot operations each of which give an improved basic feasible solution; the choice of pivot element at each step is largely determined by the requirement that this pivot improves the solution.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The following sections focus on finding the *maximum* of the objective function.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] If instead the minimum is desired, the algorithm can be modified by negating all references to the objective function.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Thus, one should select a pivot column whose the corresponding entry in the objective row ( $-{\bar {\mathbf {c} }}^{\mathrm {T} }$ ) of the tableau is negative.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] There is typically more than one column with a negative entry in the objective row, and the choice of which one to add to the set of basic variables is guided by one of several *entering variable choice rules* such as Devex algorithm.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] If none of the entries in the objective row is negative then no choice of entering variable can be made and the solution is in fact at the maximum.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Once the pivot column has been selected, the choice of pivot row is largely determined by the requirement that the resulting solution be feasible.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] First, only positive entries in the pivot column are considered, since only these lead to limits on the value of the entering variable.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] If there are no positive entries in the pivot column then the entering variable can take any non-negative value with the solution remaining feasible.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In this case the objective function is unbounded above and there is no maximum.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Next, the pivot row must be selected so that the entering variable (and hence the improvement in the objective) has maximum value subject to all the other basic variables remaining non-negative.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] is the minimum over all *r* such that ${\hat {a}}_{rc}$ > 0.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This is called the *minimum ratio test*.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] If there is more than one row for which the minimum is achieved then a *dropping variable choice rule* can be used to make the determination.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Columns 2, 3, and 4 can be selected as pivot columns.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] For this example, suppose column 4 is selected.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The values of *z* resulting from the choice of rows 2 and 3 as pivot rows are 10/1 = 10 and 15/3 = 5 respectively.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Of these the minimum is 5, so row 3 must be the pivot row.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In general, a linear program will not be given in the canonical form and an equivalent canonical tableau must be found before the simplex algorithm can start.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This can be accomplished by the introduction of *artificial variables*.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Columns of the identity matrix are added as column vectors for these variables.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] If the b value for a constraint equation is negative, the equation is negated before adding the identity matrix columns.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This does not change the set of feasible solutions or the optimal solution, and it ensures that the slack variables will constitute an initial feasible solution.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The new tableau is in canonical form but it is not equivalent to the original problem.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] So a new objective function, equal to the sum of the artificial variables, is introduced and the simplex algorithm is applied to find the minimum; the modified linear program is called the *Phase I* problem.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The simplex algorithm applied to the Phase I problem must terminate with a minimum value for the new objective function since, being the sum of nonnegative variables, its value is bounded below by 0.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] If the minimum is 0 then the artificial variables can be eliminated from the resulting canonical tableau producing a canonical tableau equivalent to the original problem.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The simplex algorithm can then be applied to find the solution; this step is called *Phase II*.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] If the minimum is positive then there is no feasible solution for the Phase I problem where the artificial variables are all zero.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This implies that the feasible region for the original problem is empty, and so the original problem has no solution.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] It differs from the previous example by having equality instead of inequality constraints.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The previous solution $x=y=0\,,z=5$ violates the first constraint.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The equation defining the original objective function is retained in anticipation of Phase II.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] By construction, *u* and *v* are both basic variables since they are part of the initial identity matrix.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] However, the objective function *W* currently assumes that *u* and *v* are both 0.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This is, fortuitously, already optimal and so the optimum value for the original linear program is 130/7.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This value is "worse" than 20 which is to be expected for a problem which is more constrained.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The tableau form used above to describe the algorithm lends itself to an immediate implementation in which the tableau is maintained as a rectangular (*m* + 1)-by-(*m* + *n* + 1) array.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] It is straightforward to avoid storing the m explicit columns of the identity matrix that will occur within the tableau by virtue of **B** being a subset of the columns of [**A**, **I**].
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This implementation is referred to as the "*standard* simplex algorithm".
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The storage and computation overhead is such that the standard simplex method is a prohibitively expensive approach to solving large linear programming problems.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In each simplex iteration, the only data required are the first row of the tableau, the (pivotal) column of the tableau corresponding to the entering variable and the right-hand-side.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The latter can be updated using the pivotal column and the first row of the tableau can be updated using the (pivotal) row corresponding to the leaving variable.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Both the pivotal column and pivotal row may be computed directly using the solutions of linear systems of equations involving the matrix **B** and a matrix-vector product using **A**.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] These observations motivate the "*revised* simplex algorithm", for which implementations are distinguished by their invertible representation of **B**.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In large linear-programming problems **A** is typically a sparse matrix and, when the resulting sparsity of **B** is exploited when maintaining its invertible representation, the revised simplex algorithm is much more efficient than the standard simplex method.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Commercial simplex solvers are based on the revised simplex algorithm.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] If the values of all basic variables are strictly positive, then a pivot must result in an improvement in the objective value.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] When this is always the case no set of basic variables occurs twice and the simplex algorithm must terminate after a finite number of steps.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Basic feasible solutions where at least one of the *basic*variables is zero are called *degenerate* and may result in pivots for which there is no improvement in the objective value.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In this case there is no actual change in the solution but only a change in the set of basic variables.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] When several such pivots occur in succession, there is no improvement; in large industrial applications, degeneracy is common and such "*stalling*" is notable.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Worse than stalling is the possibility the same set of basic variables occurs twice, in which case, the deterministic pivoting rules of the simplex algorithm will produce an infinite loop, or "cycle".
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] While degeneracy is the rule in practice and stalling is common, cycling is rare in practice.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] A discussion of an example of practical cycling occurs in Padberg.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Bland's rule prevents cycling and thus guarantees that the simplex algorithm always terminates.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Another pivoting algorithm, the criss-cross algorithm never cycles on linear programs.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] History-based pivot rules such as Zadeh's rule and Cunningham's rule also try to circumvent the issue of stalling and cycling by keeping track of how often particular variables are being used and then favor such variables that have been used least often.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The simplex method is remarkably efficient in practice and was a great improvement over earlier methods such as Fourier–Motzkin elimination.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] However, in 1972, Klee and Minty gave an example, the Klee–Minty cube, showing that the worst-case complexity of simplex method as formulated by Dantzig is exponential time.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Since then, for almost every variation on the method, it has been shown that there is a family of linear programs for which it performs badly.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] It is an open question if there is a variation with polynomial time, although sub-exponential pivot rules are known.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In 2014, it was proved that a particular variant of the simplex method is NP-mighty, i.e., it can be used to solve, with polynomial overhead, any problem in NP implicitly during the algorithm's execution.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Moreover, deciding whether a given variable ever enters the basis during the algorithm's execution on a given input, and determining the number of iterations needed for solving a given problem, are both NP-hard problems.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] At about the same time it was shown that there exists an artificial pivot rule for which computing its output is PSPACE-complete.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In 2015, this was strengthened to show that computing the output of Dantzig's pivot rule is PSPACE-complete.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Analyzing and quantifying the observation that the simplex algorithm is efficient in practice despite its exponential worst-case complexity has led to the development of other measures of complexity.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The simplex algorithm has polynomial-time average-case complexity under various probability distributions, with the precise average-case performance of the simplex algorithm depending on the choice of a probability distribution for the random matrices.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Another approach to studying "typical phenomena" uses Baire category theory from general topology, and to show that (topologically) "most" matrices can be solved by the simplex algorithm in a polynomial number of steps.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Another method to analyze the performance of the simplex algorithm studies the behavior of worst-case scenarios under small perturbation – are worst-case scenarios stable under a small change (in the sense of structural stability), or do they become tractable?
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] This area of research, called smoothed analysis, was introduced specifically to study the simplex method.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Indeed, the running time of the simplex method on input with noise is polynomial in the number of variables and the magnitude of the perturbations.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Other algorithms for solving linear-programming problems are described in the linear-programming article.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Another basis-exchange pivoting algorithm is the criss-cross algorithm.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] There are polynomial-time algorithms for linear programming that use interior point methods: these include Khachiyan's ellipsoidal algorithm, Karmarkar's projective algorithm, and path-following algorithms.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] The Big-M method is an alternative strategy for solving a linear program, using a single-phase simplex.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Cohen et al. is the representative of a branch of algorithms that apply fast matrix multiplication algorithms to linear programs.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] Linear–fractional programming (LFP) is a generalization of linear programming (LP).
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In LP the objective function is a linear function, while the objective function of a linear–fractional program is a ratio of two linear functions.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] In other words, a linear program is a fractional–linear program in which the denominator is the constant function having the value one everywhere.
[src:simplex-method-pivoting/simplex-algorithm] A linear–fractional program can be solved by a variant of the simplex algorithm or by the criss-cross algorithm.
